{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nPer-criterion **blocking is already done** (`code_review/registry.threshold_for` + kernel Pass-3 +\ndetector fail-closed). What is missing is **attestation integration**: a project criterion's\nverdict/coverage must fold into the signed (kind-keyed) attestation, and activating/editing/\ndisabling a criterion must invalidate a prior attestation — but `claim_gate_check` never\nre-compares the routing version, and `registry_version()` hashes only the PACKAGED routing\n(`attest.py:44`), so an overlay change produces an identical version and does NOT invalidate.\n\n## What\n\n- `registry_version(repo_root=None)` additionally hashes the `.rebar/` overlay when `repo_root` is\n  given; thread `repo_root` through **every** caller: `claim_gate_check` → `compute_validity`, and\n  also `drift_refresh_candidate` and `remediation_mode_candidate` (which call `registry_version()`\n  without it today). So activating/editing/disabling a criterion invalidates a prior attestation at\n  claim time.\n- A disabled built-in is recorded in a `disabled_builtins: [ids]` field in the verdict `coverage`\n  dict (folded into the signed manifest) so the cert reflects reduced coverage; additive/\n  expand-contract (absent on old certs → treated as stale → re-review, never a crash).\n- Cross-gate: this applies to **any** gate attestation backed by the shared registry — plan-review\n  now; code-review once it signs (code-review signs nothing today; the `attest.py` port to\n  code-review rides with story `#6`).\n\n## Scope\n\n- Files: `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/attest.py` (registry_version(repo_root), coverage field,\n  threading), the claim-gate path.\n- Depends on story `#1` (the overlay must exist to hash) and story `#2` (DET blocking).\n- Blocking itself is NOT in scope (already shipped via `threshold_for` + kernel Pass-3).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `registry_version(repo_root)` hashes the `.rebar/` overlay; threaded through\n      `claim_gate_check`/`compute_validity`/`drift_refresh_candidate`/`remediation_mode_candidate`.\n- [ ] Activating/editing/disabling a project criterion invalidates a prior plan-review attestation\n      at claim time; an unchanged overlay does not churn (regver == today when overlay absent).\n- [ ] A disabled built-in appears in `coverage.disabled_builtins` in the signed manifest.\n- [ ] Expand-contract: an old attestation lacking the new basis is treated as stale (re-review),\n      never a crash.\n- [ ] A project criterion's verdict + coverage fold into the signed attestation; it can never\n      rebind a built-in.\n\n\n## compute_validity regver check + disabled_builtins manifest line (remediation, run 1)\n\n### `compute_validity` gains a regver staleness check (clears G6 blocker 1)\nThreading `repo_root` into `compute_validity` is necessary but NOT sufficient — its plan-review\nbranch must ALSO compare the attestation's recorded regver against the current one:\n`manifest_regver(manifest) != registry_version(repo_root)` → the record reads as **not valid**\nwith reason `\"stale-regver\"` (a new invalidation reason alongside the existing\nmaterial/head-sha/reopen checks). So activating/editing/disabling a project criterion (which\nchanges `registry_version(repo_root)` because it now hashes the `.rebar/` overlay) makes a prior\nattestation read stale at claim time. `manifest_regver(manifest)` is a small helper that extracts\nthe `regver:` line from the signed manifest (mirroring the existing `manifest_material`). An\nattestation with NO regver line (pre-this-change) → treated as stale → re-review (expand-contract,\nnever a crash).\n\n### `disabled_builtins` is a dedicated signed manifest line (clears G6 blocker 2)\n`build_manifest()` emits a NEW `disabled_builtins: [id,id,...]` line (sorted, deterministic) WHEN\nthe verdict `coverage` carries disabled built-ins (from the overlay disabling a built-in via ef7e's\nmerge) — so the cert reflects reduced coverage rather than silent omission. A `manifest_disabled_builtins(manifest)`\nparser reads it back (like `manifest_material`). The line is ADDITIVE/expand-contract: absent on old\ncerts (parsed as `[]`), present only when non-empty, so a clean run's manifest is byte-identical to\ntoday (attestation-safe). `verify_signature` re-derives the same manifest and checks the HMAC as usual.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria (remediation additions)\n\n- [ ] `compute_validity` (plan-review branch) adds a `manifest_regver != registry_version(repo_root)`\n      staleness check returning reason `stale-regver`; a missing regver line → stale (re-review).\n      A test proves activating/editing a project criterion invalidates a prior attestation.\n- [ ] `build_manifest` emits a deterministic `disabled_builtins: [ids]` line when the verdict\n      coverage has disabled built-ins; a `manifest_disabled_builtins` parser reads it; absent/empty\n      on a clean run (byte-identical manifest). A test asserts the round-trip + HMAC re-verify.\n\n\n## No mass re-review + the built-in-disable mechanism (remediation, run 2)\n\n### The regver line ALREADY exists — no mass invalidation (clears T4)\nCurrent signed manifests ALREADY carry a `regver:` line (verified: e.g. `regver: 83e5f63ad06d893a`).\nThis story adds the CHECK in `compute_validity`, NOT the line. The `registry_version` basis change is\nADDITIVE: for an OVERLAY-ABSENT repo, `registry_version(repo_root)` hashes the same packaged routing\nit does today ⇒ the SAME regver value ⇒ existing certs stay valid (zero churn). A repo that has an\noverlay is BY DEFINITION new (the overlay feature shipped in ef7e), so it has NO pre-existing certs to\ninvalidate. The truly-ancient \"no regver line at all\" case → stale → one re-review, which is the\ncorrect expand-contract behaviour (never a crash). So there is no deployment-wide mandatory re-review.\n\n### The built-in-disable mechanism is part of THIS story (clears G6)\nef7e's MVP implemented overlay RE-TUNE of a built-in (per-key routing merge) but NOT disable. This\nstory adds disable: an overlay `plan_review` entry for a BUILT-IN id carrying `\"disabled\": true`\nREMOVES that built-in from `effective_criteria(repo_root)` (so its finder never runs) — implemented\nin `registry.effective_criteria` (a disabled built-in is excluded from the returned set) +\n`effective_routing` (the entry is retained but flagged). The set of disabled built-in ids is exposed\nvia a small `disabled_builtins(repo_root) -> list[str]` helper. The gate records them in the verdict\n`coverage[\"disabled_builtins\"]`, which `build_manifest` folds into the `disabled_builtins:` manifest\nline. `_validate_routing_entry` accepts `disabled: bool` only on an un-prefixed (built-in) id (a\n`project.` id cannot be \"disabled\" — it is simply not activated). This keeps the epic's \"the overlay\nmay re-tune OR disable a built-in; a disable is recorded in coverage\" AC coherent within this story.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria (remediation additions, run 2)\n\n- [ ] Overlay-absent repos see NO regver change (existing attestations stay valid); the regver line\n      already exists, so this adds only the staleness CHECK. A test asserts overlay-absent parity.\n- [ ] An overlay `disabled: true` on a built-in id removes it from `effective_criteria`; a\n      `disabled_builtins(repo_root)` helper lists them; they flow into `coverage` + the manifest line.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782887238013210001,"uuid":"7760aaef-554e-4ce1-bcdb-29e7fc60a013"}